        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria — Gradation 3 production-representative sample",
        "description": "N ≥ 10 constructs from production lots, tested across ≥ 2 independent laboratories. Sample traceability documented (lot numbers, dimensional inspection). Coefficient of variation for experimental stiffness < 8%."
      },
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot components (screw lot 2022-07-A, rod lot 2022-07-B) tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH Biomechanics Lab and DePuy Synthes R&D). Full traceability maintained via component serial numbers. Experimental stiffness CV=5.3%, yield force CV=4.8%, both within acceptance bounds. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "ASTM F1717 fully specifies the compression-bending test configuration — fixture geometry, loading rate (5 mm/min displacement control), environmental conditions (ambient, dry), and specimen preparation — leaving no meaningful degrees of freedom for varying test conditions within the standard. The validation objective is to demonstrate model fidelity against the F1717 protocol as used in regulatory submissions, not to characterise model performance across a range of loading environments. Varying temperature, humidity, or loading rate would generate data outside the regulatory submission envelope and would not improve credibility for the intended COU. Furthermore, the multi-laboratory design (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes) already captures inter-laboratory variability in test execution, which is the primary source of test-condition uncertainty for a standardised protocol. Scoping out this factor is therefore justified on the grounds that (a) the test protocol is fully prescribed by consensus standard, (b) the COU is explicitly bounded to F1717 conditions, and (c) the regulatory precedent for pedicle screw submissions does not require multi-condition validation when a standardised test method is employed. This scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team on 2024-11-15."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-equiv-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
